.TH "STRIP\-EXT" "1" "March 2026" "" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
strip\-ext \- remove the final filename extension from matching files
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]strip\-ext\f[R] [\-n] [\-h] pattern \&...
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]strip\-ext\f[R] renames each matching file by removing only its
last filename extension.
.PP
For example, \f[CR]archive.tar.gz\f[R] becomes \f[CR]archive.tar\f[R],
not \f[CR]archive\f[R].
.PP
Existing destination paths are never overwritten.
Files without an extension are skipped.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R]
Dry run.
Print what would be renamed without making any changes.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R]
Show usage help and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
strip\-ext \[aq]*.sh\[aq]
strip\-ext \-n \[aq]*.tar.gz\[aq]
strip\-ext report.txt archive.tar.gz
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
No files matched, invalid usage, or another error occurred.
.SH NOTES
Only the last extension segment is removed.
.SH SEE ALSO
\f[B]mv\f[R](1)
